		<wp:meta_value><![CDATA[Dear Dr. Schulze,

First, I just want to say thank you for the time and effort you have put into your products and your practice. I'm suffering from candida right now, and cannot wait to do your bowel cleanse. The good you have accomplished is really remarkable. 

Second, and I hope you don't just brush this off as a ridiculous message from someone who doesn't know what she's talking about, or doesn't know what's best for everyone, but I just have to say that I was a little disappointed in the way you addressed the letter you got from Joe in your lightening round video answering (some weird) questions. 

Just to jog your memory, he was the one that went on and on about sex and STDs and how it's terrible and you're terrible and blah blah blah. I realize that he really does seem to need therapy, or at least some sort of help, perhaps in more areas than one, but I have to say, I was saddened to hear the way you responded. 

I guess I feel that one, you could have been gentler in your response. It came off as very harsh (like a lot of your videos do). Actually I think in general, that's a good thing, because it does make more of an impact. In this case, however, where the subject is such a sensitive one for many, I think your response was not ideal. 

For instance, many Christians believe that sex before marriage, or sex with people who you do not love (even if they are healthy), is morally wrong. I know many Christians who, if they did or do have sex, say, before marriage, feel very ashamed, guilty, and upset with themselves. Now whether you believe this is bull shit or not, doesn't matter. 

The bottom line is, if they themselves have sex, this leads to a lot of spiritual unrest, and consequent health issues. 

I know you're big on not only physical health, but spiritual health (and I love that about you), so I guess I would just like to encourage you to think about the fact that your viewers have varied opinions on sex. 

While it may be physically healthier to have sex (you're spot on with that), the fact of the matter is, it may be spiritually more detrimental for some to do so. 

Now please don't get me wrong, I think you should still share your opinion as well - after all, it's valid, and if everyone else is allowed to have an opinion on sex, so is Dr. Schulze - but what I'm saying is, perhaps you can share it in a gentler manner. 

I hope that should this topic come up again, you will make it known that you respect that people have varying views on the moral implications of sex. Make it known that you respect their moral implications, and that you are addressing the physical implications. 

My respect for you would increase, and I know others' would as well. 

God bless you, Dr. Schulze!

Sincerely,

Elizabeth from Germany
eleitzmann@gmail.com]]></wp:meta_value>
