		<wp:meta_value><![CDATA[Dear Dr. Schulze, I just listened to your blog on soy and BPA's.  Was hoping that you would also expound on soy as it pertains to hormones.  I've heard and read, from what would seem good authority, on both sides, that soy helps not to cause breast cancer; and also heard that soy does help to cause breast cancer or cancer in general.  Also read that soy causes hypothyroidism.  I researched about this because I came down with an ovarian cyst (which ruptured).  But was very sick and missed at least a month from work.  Read that soy can mess with the hormones, as it is like putting estrogen in your body, and can cause an imbalance if you don't have enough progesterone to balance it out, and which, for one, can cause the growth of an ovarian cyst.  I had soy because I like it, but stopped having it.  Never got another cyst.

I'm now at the menopause age, and it seems that soy would be a good thing, if it gives you more estrogen, or worked like estrogen.  I'm not on hormones; want to do natural.  I've read a lot of your literature, do the cleanses, and live the health principles... vegan, mostly raw...  clean water, exercise, sunlight, etc.  Am always striving for improvement; seems I can always improve on something.

Am feeling and seeing the effects of being at my young-yet-getting-older age; skin thinner, little wrinkles, hair a little thinner...  I'll stop there.  I had heard that these symptoms are from having less estrogen in the body.  So I purposely then drank unsweetened soy milk, and took a soy supplement, both of which made me feel kind of yucky, for lack of a better word.  I've experimented with soy over the past year, and without a doubt I have found that if I have any soy, within the hour I get a hot flash.  If I stay away from soy, and stay away from refined foods with a lot of ingredients, like crackers, breads, etc., I don't get hot flashes.

I would really like your opinion on soy, as it relates to hormones, if it helps with estrogen levels.  And if so, is that a good or bad thing.

And does your Female tonic help balance hormones, on the estrogen and progesterone aspects; does it help to balance both?

Thank you!  And thank you for the blogs!
Terry G.
