My husband recently discovered that his family has, for generations, been effected by Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome Type IV, also known as Vascular Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome. In this very rare disease, connective tissues are built weak, resulting in rupturing blood vessels and rupturing hollow organs—often in persons as young as their mid-30s. (My husband is 38.) Study has shown that the DNA is "wrong" in a strand for Collagen 3, which literally builds everything from blood vessels and muscles to tooth enamel. 

So, please—do you have any advice on how a body that is "programmed" wrong might heal itself? Also, as you overcame a genetic heart deformity, would you have any suggestions on how my husband (and, now, our 3 young children, who are likely at risk) might attempt to keep arteries and the vascular system strong?

