		<wp:post_parent>0</wp:post_parent>
		<wp:menu_order>0</wp:menu_order>
		<wp:post_type>Question</wp:post_type>
		<wp:post_password></wp:post_password>
		<wp:is_sticky>0</wp:is_sticky>
								<wp:postmeta>
		<wp:meta_key>mf_post_question</wp:meta_key>
		<wp:meta_value><![CDATA[Dear Dr. Schulze,
Thank you for all that you do and have done for the health of all that will listen to you.  We are experiencing an issue that I hope that you can shed some light on.  We have been doing your gallbladder/liver cleanse for 5 days with your products and as close to what your instructions are as we can.   On the evening of the first day of the cleanse my husband had a nose bleed so we sat him down and immediately took his blood pressure and repeated the blood pressure a few times.  It was a little high when he first sat down, however you are suppose to relax and sit a minute before doing a blood pressure.  Blood pressure range was and is 120/68 to 150/98.  The blood pressure is normal when we take a resting blood pressure.  

Note that my husband has no history of nosebleeds until this cleanse and I am not implying the cleanse caused it, we just need your thoughts.  

We read online that nose bleeds caused by blood pressure are usually further back in the nose (posterior nose bleed).  This bleed was forward in the nose and he has had nose bleeds every day while on the cleanse.  None of the following common causes listed below apply to my husband.  We take food supplements but do not take any drugs, legal or illegal and only drink a glass a wine a few times in a year.  	
▪	Causes of anterior nosebleeds
	▪	Sometimes, the cause of anterior nosebleeds is idiopathic (unknown). However, common causes include: 	
	▪	Blowing your nose hard - also blowing your nose too frequently
	▪	Picking the inside of your nose - especially if this is done often, if the fingernails are long, and if the inside of the nose is already irritated or tender.
	▪	A knock or blow to the nose - could damage the delicate blood vessels of the mucous membrane.
	▪	Sinusitis - an inflammation of the sinuses (air-filled cavities of the bone and skull surrounding the nose)
	▪	A cold or flu - this could be for various reasons. Partly because people with colds and flu blow their nose more often - nose blowing raises the risk of nosebleeds. The inside of the nose may be irritated and tender during a vital infection, making it more susceptible to bleeding.
	▪	Deviated septum - when the wall separating the two nostrils is off center, or deviated.
	▪	Climate - hot climates with low humidity or changes from bitter cold to warm, dry climates can cause drying and cracking inside the nose, which can lead to a nosebleed.
	▪	High altitude - as altitude increases, the availability of oxygen decreases, making the air thinner and drier. The dryness could cause the nose to bleed.
	▪	Nasal allergies.
	▪	Excessive use of certain kinds of medications, such as anticoagulants (blood thinners) or non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) like Ibuprofen.
	▪	Liver disease can interfere with blood clotting and result in frequent and/or severe nosebleeds.
	▪	Excessive use of illegal drugs, such as cocaine.   

We are continuing to juice and eat raw food and hope to understand what is happening.  We also read that nose bleeds can be a symptom of liver disease.  We need to know how to proceed.  We were going to wait a few days and start the kidney cleanse and then do the cold sheet treatment per your instructions.  We have done all this before a little over a year ago.  We also have done your colon cleanse. 

We are both natural health care practitioners and use your products in our office.  We are stumped on this issue and look forward to hearing your wisdom.  

If you publish this please use our initials.  Thanks!

Maureen

Maureen Hays, RN
Doug Hays, DC]]></wp:meta_value>
		</wp:postmeta>
