		<wp:meta_value><![CDATA[Dear Dr. Schulze,

I just had an ultra sound imaging exam of my legs and I am diagnosed with PAD (peripheral arterial disease). I have had it for about 4 years but never to this extent. One week ago I did an intense lower body (legs) workout at the gym using the weight machines. Since that time my right leg has been very numb, cold, some discoloration and with extreme pain (all mainly in my lower leg and foot). The ultra sound imaging results today showed that my femoral artery is severely blocked and one of the arteries in my lower leg has no blood flow. My doctor said that the amount of blood flow to my leg and foot is very bad and only a ‘trickle’. If I don’t attend to it immediately and see a vascular surgeon, that I will lose my leg. I have not seen or been able to make an appointment with the vascular surgeon, but I am almost sure that they will recommend some invasive procedure such as a stent or angioplast, etc. My question is, I guess, is there some other noninvasive way, e.g., following your dietary protocols; how much time would it take to turn this condition around; can it be turned around and how much time before it really becomes worse to the point of amputation.

Thank you]]></wp:meta_value>
