		<wp:meta_key>mf_post_question</wp:meta_key>
		<wp:meta_value><![CDATA[Dear Dr. Schulze,
I was considering purchasing both your "Heart Formula" and "K-B Formula".  However, I was wondering if you knew if the herbs that each formula contained were safe to take with a liver transplant?  I had a liver transplant in the year 2000 due to having Primary Biliary Cirrhosis.  I take the "Neoral" brand of Cyclosprine Modified, 100 mg twice a day, for my immuosuppressant drug.  I have to be careful as to what I take both in prescription drugs and herbs due to possible interactions.  I currently can not take St. Johns Wort or Enchinacea for both are known to cause liver rejection with transplant patients.  Also, grapefruit juice has to be avoided due to raising the cyclosporine levels to toxic levels.

I currently have high blood pressure due to the cyclosporine.  I also have recurrent urinary tract  infections.  The cyclosporine as well as the recurrent urinary tract infections has caused my kidneys to really decline in the past 9 months.  I need to get the urinary tract infections under control or the antibiotics are going to destroy my kidneys.  I have bee diagnosed as having Stage 4 kidney disease at this time due to my Glomerular Filtration Rate being 22.  It went from 40 to 22 in a matter of 6 months.  I also have a low red blood count, my hematocrit is low and my platelet count is low.

I do not like taking drugs and had a lot of bad side effects from them.  I have been on 10 different antibiotic prescriptions since January 19, 2014 for urinary tract infections.  I took Bactrim (once), Amoxicillin (twice), Cephalexin (3 times), Ciprofloxacin (twice), Macrobid (once) and now Septra(once).  When I complete a prescription, a urinary tract infection re-occurs 2-3 weeks later.  Cephalexin caused me to have several hematomas on my arms and legs as well as hives.  Ciprofloxacin cause me to throw up and Macrobid caused severe headaches.  All these antibiotics are known to be bad for the kidneys and I can see by my blood work that my kidney function got worse especially when taking Cephalexin and Ciprofloxacin.  It states in the cyclosporine drug pamplet that Ciprofloxacin can cause kidney failure when taken together.  However, my liver transplant physician prescribed Ciprofloxacin twice even when I brought it to his attention.  Macrobid is not supposed to be taken if one has any decreased kidney function, yet a urologist prescribed this drug.

As far as blood pressure medications, I tried avoiding these as long as I could.  However, I ended up in the emergency room several times due to my blood pressure being 208/105.  I was prescribed Carvedilol 3.125 mg twice a day but stopped taking it after one week for it made me feel sedated, dizzy and my breathing seemed shallow.  Plus, I do not want to take a beta blocker for blood pressure for one can not just stop taking a beta blocker, for it could cause a heart attack if one does.  I was on Lisinopril 2.5 mg one a day for just a few days but stopped taking it due to the feeling that I could not breathe as well.  I was then put on Amlidopine 10 mg a day.  However, it made my legs and feet swell excessively.  The dosage was then dropped to one 2.5 mg pill a day.  I have been taking "Amlidopine 2.5 mg one a day" for the past two months.  My blood pressure is now anywhere in the 140's-150's over the mid to upper 80's.  I still have some swelling (fluid retention) in my legs and feet due to the Amlidopine.

I need your advice as to what I can do to keep my blood pressure down as well as preventing re-current urinary tract infections.  I do not want to take all these drugs.  Prior to my liver transplant, I did not even take an aspirin.  I would welcome any advice you can give as to how to reduce my blood pressure and to prevent re-current urinary tract infections.  Please keep in mind that I have had a liver transplant, I am anemic, hematocrit is low and my platelet count is low (which causes me to bleed more easily).

If I can take the "Heart Formula", please advise me of the dosage and how often to take it.

Also, would the "Cayenne Tincture" be good to take, taking into consideration that my platelet count is low.

If I can take the "K-B Formula", please advise me of the dosage and how often to take it as well.  Should I take it like 5-7 days once a month?

Also, if you have any suggestions on what my diet should be (what foods to include or to avoid for both high blood pressure and urinary tract infections and what foods to eat to get adequate protein in my diet, it would be greatly  appreciated.  

Thank you.]]></wp:meta_value>
