I am a 46 year old woman that has fought hypothyroid disease, irritable bowel, fatty liver, and chronic low back pain.  During my quest to find answers to why I always felt tired, chronic pain, and stomach issues I found out during an ultrasound of my stomach that my left kidney was atrophic (which the kidney specialist said it was shrunk and didn't function.  They did another ultrasound on the other kidney to make sure it was functioning and it was.  He said I should be ok since I only need one kidney to survive.It was discouraging to say the least since he really couldn't give me any answers as to why one kidney had stopped working and was shrunk.  Maybe an infection when I was younger that went untreated was the cause but no real answers.  In the meantime, with all the pain in my back I was introduced to pain killers to deal with the pain and it helped!  I felt like doing things for the first time in a long time and didn't hurt as much so I started leaning on them as a way to function and feel energized. I had always felt such a lag in my energy level and fought "feeling blah all the time".  It was hard to get up in the mornings without making myself crawl out of bed and make myself get thru the workday.  What could it hurt, they are prescription pills anyway, right?  Three years later I found myself addicted to the pain meds and not thinking of what these pills might be doing to my body (especially my kidney and liver).  I am tired of this viscous cycle and have tried to stop taking the pain meds but every time I do I get so sick and cant seem to get myself back on the right track.  Please give me some guidance on how to safely stop taking the pain pills and still be able to go to work and address the above issues (hypothyroid, fatty liver, and chronic low back pain).  I am desperate to change my lifestyle and feel "good" naturally.  Is there anything out there to minimize the withdrawal symptoms of coming off the pain pills and still allow me to function on my job and daily life duties?  What is the best plan of action to regain energy, have the will to get up and face the day, and get that joy of living back in my life? If I had to say what the most critical first step for me would be how to get thru the withdrawals that come when you stop taking narcotics after years of daily use.  I am not trying to sound suicidal or anything because I am not but I just feel so discouraged and disappointed in myself for letting my life spiral out of control.  Thank you for any direction you can give me to improve my quality of life.  
