		<wp:meta_value><![CDATA[7]]></wp:meta_value>
		</wp:postmeta>
				<wp:postmeta>
		<wp:meta_key>mf_post_question</wp:meta_key>
		<wp:meta_value><![CDATA[Dear Dr. Schulze,

First I like to begin by thanking you for keeping me alive. Following an MI in 1998 at the ripe old age of 48. I began your program and have never looked back. CAYENNE - YES!!! ... POOPING - YES!!!!!!

Recently received the following from a friend and immediately thought of you.
I do realize you're very well connected but thought in the event you may have missed this I'd make sure you didn't. Enjoy and Thanks again for all your inspiration.

An interesting story has New Yorkers buzzing. Columbia University student Emma Sulkowicz is carrying a mattress with her everywhere she goes.
She will continue to do this as long as her alleged rapist remains on campus.
Emma is a visual arts major and the mattress doubles as her powerful statement and as her senior thesis project.
Emma says, “The past year of my life has been really marked by telling people what happened in that most intimate and private space. I was raped in my own dorm bed. That space has become fraught for me. I feel like I’ve carried the weight of what happened there since then.”

I read about this and it made me both angry and liberated. 
Angry because the alleged rapist has been accused of rape by two other women, yet still walks freely around the university campus.
Liberated because we all have burdens that we bear deep in our body. 
The difference between most of us (myself included) and Emma is that she is choosing to exorcise her burden.

These burdens that we all carry are the root of our struggles. As goes the ancient teaching, "Congestion is the basis of sickness. Circulation is the basis of healing."

When fears, resentments, and pain get stuck deep within us, they impede the flow of life. 
But when you uproot that which is stuck, you liberate...and heal.
Even better, by working through your own sh*t, you inspire others to work through theirs.  
Last night, I went to Rosh Hashanah services and the rabbi said something in his sermon. "Whatever your religion, it's important to take a more religious outlook on life."
By that, he meant, see life for what it is...a beautiful journey filled with lessons that are only learned when we ask, out loud, "What is the meaning of all this?" 
Are you really supposed to live in a state of struggle?
Are you really supposed to always feel tired?
Are you really supposed to always worry?
Ask those questions out loud and the answer is so obvious.
Personally, I am a terribly insecure person.  It has been buried within me ever since the "acne-on-my-face, hairspray-in-the-do, braces-on-the-teeth, freckle-on-the-lip" stage that I endured as a kid.
I ask out loud, "Am I really supposed to feel insecure the rest of my life?"
And here is the answer. 
Hell no!
If Emma Sulkowicz can carry a frickin’ mattress around New York City, I can deal with my own sh*t and so can you. It may be a process and it may take time, but it starts by holding high above you that which has always festered deep within you.]]></wp:meta_value>
		</wp:postmeta>
