		<wp:meta_key>mf_post_question</wp:meta_key>
		<wp:meta_value><![CDATA[Dear Dr. Schulze,
I recently saw your video  about chronic childhood constipation & the surgeries to do colostomies.  My daughter suffered from the sane chronic condition since age 2, which abruptly began, and finally we resorted to an appendicostomy (stoma via appendix) w/no resection or bowel removal. Very long story that involved 3 major pediatric top medical facilities & several gastro specialists for 10+ yrs, we resorted to finally opt for surgical relief. Unlike many of your other clients letters, our daughter is finally healthy & happy.  Her surgery doesn't require a bag, but she catheterize a & flushes each day. If she poops in her own, it can be skipped. The stoma is discreetly concealed in her belly button & she has no bandages or leakage. It's a step we tried to avoid for a long time. She'd been dairy free, gluten free, we literally counted fiber intake, avoided junk food & used Formula 3 & 1.... Unfortunately no lasting impressive results. She'd been hospitalized 9 times in 3 yrs for impaction lasting over 2 wks. We would've been so willing & grateful to have corrected this w/diet & herbs & I can confidently say we diligently gave it a fair shot over a decade. Finally, my daughter began asking for relief. How her life was affected emotionally & physically over 10 yrs is long & sad. We saw a neuro muscular pediatric gastro specialist that did a colonic manometry which revealed no muscle/nerve function, a test done over 7 hours.  Her colon did respond to Bisacoydl but was injected via catheter directly into intestine. Bingo! Results! She'd tried it orally over the years & of course enemas only reach a few inches. She has good predictably happy days. She remains underweight & has a ways to go to catch up there. I'd welcome any suggestions you have for that. I use your formula 1 & believe in your approach, but have had to blend it w/the medical world. I had to help our ailing daughter. I thought you deserved to hear a good report on a surgical alternative. As our daughter grows, she too can incorporate herbs & may someday be able to discontinue use of the appendicostomy. For now, only 5 months new, we are over the moon happy to not have the daily worry & stress of the constipation that ruled & ruined our daughters peace of mind. To have a child that consistently feels well us a luxury I'm just now realizing. Our daughter is 13, beautiful & happy. Thank you for what you do. Your input is welcomed. Julie ]]></wp:meta_value>
