		<wp:meta_key>mf_post_question</wp:meta_key>
		<wp:meta_value><![CDATA[Dear Dr. Schulze,

I am at a loss.  I have worms and don't know what to do about it.  Whilst I have suspected for about 7 years that there was something living inside me, they suddenly became very obvious about a year ago.  However, considering historical symptoms I now know to be linked to the worms, I suspect I have had them since I was a child, well over 40 years (I'm 57).

Whilst they may be in my gut, I have never seen any in my stool, well not obvious, but they are systemic in my body.  The larger ones are in my left side and upper back, the juveniles and larva go all over my body, around my face and scalp, down my arms and legs, buttocks, bile duct, everywhere.  If they were just in my gut, they might have departed by now, but they are around my body with no intention of giving up their nice little eco-system.

I can feel them.  I am not in the least delusional.  Writhing, biting, squirming, knotting, wriggling, are not normal body sensations....  They are most active at night, and Full Moon.  I have tried throwing different traditional remedies, herbs and foods at them, but they just shrug them off.  If they feel in the least threatened, they just hatch more eggs.  Apart from the fact my doctor can't do anything without 'proof', and my two stool tests have both come back negative, I really don't want to take toxic drugs.  Even if they could kill them, do I really want a body filled with dead and decaying worms?

I am diabetic, diagnosed in 1997, on insulin since 2003.  I managed to dump BP drugs and Metformin since changing my diet to Low carb, gluten free, and reverse neuropathy, restless legs, IBS, hot flushes, sweats, palpitations, liver spots, Candida, etc., through diet and vitamins, but these things have gotten me beat.  About 5 months ago I developed a dry tongue tip.  Ok in the morning, but sticks to my bottom front teeth during the day and won't leave them alone.  They and my tongue feel 'raspy'. I don't think my mouth is dry, but it feels it.  It's weird.  It could be linked, after all these worms are feeding and defecating in me all the time.....and I wouldn't be in the least surprised if they are behind the diabetes.  They seem to be very adept at disrupting sugar metabolism for their own ends.

I am pretty sure the worms are Ascaris.  I broke my leg last year and had to have it pinned in an op.  I could feel the beggars sliding in and out of the wound and when the cast was removed, there were squiggly worm tracks in the dry skin on my leg.  I also had narrow itchy welts come up on my thigh as the worms fled from the anaesthetic block that was put in my groin.  I get continuous dead larva, thin hair with a blob on one end 'floaters' in my eyes, and feel the sharp needle pain as one goes through my eyeball occasionally.  I feel them tickling as they move around my face, especially around my eyes.

Although desperately tired at night, I am frightened to lay down as they put the music on and start the party.  It's often 3 or 4 in the morning before I can begin to rest.  Whilst 'foreign' countries are very aware of the parasite issue that faces all creatures, the US and here in the UK seems oblivious.  'Have you been 'abroad' recently?  No, and neither's the dog, but he can get them (not that I have a dog, but you get my drift.....)'. I really feel this is a very underestimated and hidden issue, and may well be behind a lot of our modern ills.

I know the answer lies in rebalancing and strengthening the body, but these things are eating me out of house and home, constantly undermining my efforts to regain my health.  I struggle to get enough nutrition for myself even with supplements.  It's frustrating to have got so far in my healing process and not be able to go any further.  I just don't know what to do.  

Any advice would be very welcome.  Thank you.]]></wp:meta_value>
