I recently had a patient who had a 'twisted bowel' a few months ago. She had surgery to take out part of her large intestine (I don't know how much). After this healed up, she had another 'blockage' and another surgery. This time she was told that it was part of her small intestine that was twisted and the surgeon was able to untwist it so he didn't have to cut it out. She then came to me to find out what I can do. She told me that she has been very constipated all her life and even though she is in her late 50's, she looks like she is in her 80's. This tells me that her gut is in very bad shape and not absorbing nutrients properly, especially protein and fats. It also tells me a lot of other things about her health that is too long to list here, but we beginning to put together a plan to help her.

My question for you is, is it OK to give her your Formula 1 with the senna to help her peristaltic muscle contraction and get her bowels moving again, or am I potentially going to cause another twisted bowel. I told her that the reason she is in this shape in the first place is because her intestines were too weak from years of disuse. If she was having normal healthy peristaltic activity throughout her bowels she probably would not have had this problem. I want to help this patient but don't want to cause another episode.

Thanks, 
Dr. Don Baune]]></wp:meta_value>
